 Feb 1969":"21 February 1969","1390":"1390","1337":"1337","1304":"1304","1324":"1324","1334":"1334","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","about 1359":"about 1359","about 1334":"about 1334","about 1361":"about 1361","25 Jan 1969":"25 January 1969","Of, Cople, Bedfordshire, England":"Cople, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Turvey, Bedfordshire, England":"Turvey, Bedfordshire, England","Cople, Bedfordshire, England":"Cople, Bedfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fortis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian (mainly Piedmont): patronymic from the personal name   Forte  . It is formed with the Latin ablative plural suffix <i>-is</i> imparting the sense ‘belonging to, of’, in this case ‘member of the Forti family’ (compare   Forti  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Forte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Antonio, Carmine, Rocco, Guido, Salvatore, Aldo, Gaetano, Pasquale, Carlo, Matteo, Annamaria.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Forte</i>, from Late Latin <i>fortis</i> ‘strong, brave’ (see   Fort   2) or from a short form of a medieval personal name formed with this element, as for example <i>Fortebraccio</i> (‘strong arm’).","Italian: nickname from <i>forte</i> ‘strong’. Compare   Lo Forte  ."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":3,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":48,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Ellen Fortis was born about 1334, in Turvey, Bedfordshire, England, her father, Sampson Fortis, was 36 and her mother, Mrs Fortis, was 31. She married Osbert de Mordaunt III about 1359, in Cople, Bedfordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"about 1334–":"umbes 1334–Surnud","1334–Female":"1334–Surnud","1330–1360":"1330–1360","1360–1390":"1360–1390","1361–Male":"1361–Surnud","1300–1334":"1300–1334","1304–Female":"1304–Surnud","1330":"1330","1361":"1361","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","21 Feb 1969":"21. veebruar 1969","1390":"1390","1337":"1337","1304":"1304","1324":"1324","1334":"1334","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","about 1359":"umbes 1359","about 1334":"umbes 1334","about 1361":"umbes 1361","25 Jan 1969":"25. jaanuar 1969","Of, Cople, Bedfordshire, England":"Cople, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Turvey, Bedfordshire, England":"Tu